<br>
I won't address the 1st two points since neither of us have the ability to prove anything.  I will assume that Iraq posses weapons of mass destruction for the rest of my arguments.<br>
<br>
I know of at least 10 countries that posses nuclear weapons and I'm sure there are at least another 10 that have chemical and/or biological weapons.  Should we force a country to disarm solely based upon their ability to cause mass destruction?  Should we disarm using that logic?<br>
<br>
I believe we will have far more American casualties in any new war with Iraq as we will be fighting in Iraq and not merely trying to expel them from another country.  Also, the last 2 major terrorist actions on US soil perpetrated by foreign agents were by Bin Laden's group.  There is very little if any connection between Bin Laden and Iraq seeing as how Osama and Sadaam don't agree on much religiously or philisophically.  There is however a long association between Bin Laden and Saudi Arabia, should we force them to disarm?  <br>
<br>
As for the increase in terrorism, it will increase in direct relation to our increasing involvement in Arab affairs.  If we don't want to give them a reason to hate us all we have to do is withdraw and leave them alone.  This won't happen since our government decided long ago that lower gas prices are far more important than a country's or region's sovereignty.<br>
<br>
As for CNN, wrong!  That network is too biased for my taste.  I watch Fox news as well as read the paper and internet.  I don't let any one news organization or individual provide all my news as no one is able to do that without at least some bias.  So I learn what I can and make my own judgements based on the facts that are presented.<br>
